[[Image:Migunov caricature.jpg|right]]

'''Evgeniy Tikhonovich Migunov''' ({{lang-ru|Евге́ний Ти́хонович Мигуно́в}}; February 27, 1921 – January 1, 2004) was a Russian artist, animator and cartoonist.

In the 1950s he worked in [[Soyuzmultfilm]], but was fired over noncompliance with company's policy (he tried to implement several innovations). Later he worked at "Diafilm", a children's book publisher, at the satiric magazine ''[[Krokodil]]'', and ''Vesyolye kartinki'' magazine.

Among his major achievements are illustrations to [[Alexander Melentyevich Volkov|Aleksandr Volkov]] novels on Emerald City and [[Kir Bulychov]]'s novels, most notably, the ''[[Alisa Selezneva]]'' series. He used his animation experience to create a "motion blur" effect in his works.

Migunov illustrations for [[Boris and Arkady Strugatsky|Strugatsky Brothers']] ''[[Monday Begins on Saturday]]'' and ''The [[Tale of the Troika]]'' are considered by many an inalienable part of the novels.

